            <biogHist>
                <p>Donald Mackay was born in Creich, Sutherland, the eldest son of Hugh MacKay,
                    farmer, and Janet, n√©e Ross. He was educated at the University of Glasgow and
                    was ordained to Tarbert Mission, Harris in 1850. He married Mary Macdonald (died
                    at Nigg Manse, 7 September 1925), daughter of Roderick Macdonald, in 1859. They
                    had 6 children: Catherine Hughina, b. ll February 1860 (married William
                    Robertson, naval engineer); Jessie, b. ll January 1862 (married Newall, tacksman
                    of Aignish, Lewis); Jemima, b. 24 May 1864 (married Kenneth Mackenzie, Provost
                    of Stornoway); Roderick John, medical practitioner, b. 3 October 1866; Norman
                    Donald, minister of Nigg, b. 28 December 1871; and Elizabeth Isabella Mary, b.
                    23 December 1877. He was translated to Cross on 8 May 1861, and was translated
                    and admitted on 7 August 1878. Donald Mackay was demitted on 1 October 1891 and
                    died at Stornoway 6 July 1893 due to senile decay; his son Norman Mackay being
                    present at his death.</p>
                <p>Carmichael collected a song entitled 'Gearan an t-Sealgair'' from Donald in
                    October 1873.</p>
